## Key Points

- Bash is a command-line environment for interacting with the operating system.
- `pwd`, `ls`, and `cd` are the most fundamental navigation commands.
- Paths can be absolute or relative.
- `mkdir`, `cp`, `mv`, and `rm` are essential for file and directory management.
- `>` overwrites a file, while `>>` appends to it.
- Pipes make it possible to chain simple commands into useful workflows.
- `sort`, `cut`, `uniq`, `wc`, `head`, and `tail` are core text-processing tools.
- `uniq` only works on adjacent duplicate lines, so it is often used after `sort`.
- `for` loops are the starting point for automation and batch processing.
- Learning Bash is less about memorizing every command and more about understanding how to combine small commands to solve problems efficiently.

